-- Indian Rupee Approaches Two-Week Low on Output Slump; Bonds Gain
-- B y   J e a n e t t e   R o d r i g u e s
-- 2013-11-05T05:06:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-05/indian-rupee-approaches-two-week-low-on-output-slump-bonds-gain.html
India ’s rupee fell toward a two-week
low on speculation demand for the nation’s assets will decline
after manufacturing contracted for a third month. Bonds rose.  A purchasing managers’ index compiled by HSBC Holdings Plc
and Markit Economics was unchanged at 49.6 in October, below the
50 level that marks the dividing line between expansion and
contraction, according to a Nov. 1 report. HSBC and Markit will
publish today the latest reading for a similar gauge for
services industries that fell to 44.6 in September. The S&P BSE
Sensex Index of shares fell 0.9 percent today after climbing to
a record in a special trading session on Nov. 3. Local markets
were shut yesterday for a holiday.  “The rupee will be data-driven,” said Naveen Raghuvanshi,
a trader at Development Credit Bank Ltd. in Mumbai. “There’s
also profit-booking in equities and that will affect the
 exchange rate .”  The rupee declined 0.2 percent from Nov. 1 to 61.8350 per
dollar as of 10 a.m. in Mumbai, according to prices from local
banks compiled by Bloomberg. The currency touched 61.95 earlier,
approaching a Nov. 1 low of 61.965 that was the weakest since
Oct. 15. The rupee’s losses will be limited as exporters
repatriate earnings, Raghuvanshi predicted.  One-month implied volatility in the rupee, a gauge of
expected moves in the exchange rate used to price options,
dropped two basis points from yesterday to 10.97 percent.  The yield on the 7.16 percent government notes due May 2023
fell two basis points, or 0.02 percentage point, from Nov. 1 to
8.69 percent, according to prices from the central bank’s
trading system.  Economic Outlook  India’s economy  will grow 5 percent in the year through
March 2014, the central bank forecast last week, matching the
previous period’s pace that was the slowest since 2003.  Global funds bought a net $2.9 billion of Indian shares in
October, exchange data show, spurred by the U.S. Federal
Reserve’s record monetary stimulus. Local traders made
ceremonial purchases of stocks in a special trading session on
Nov. 3 to mark the Diwali festival and the start of the Hindu
new year. The session is held every year and is deemed the most
auspicious time to start investments.  Three-month onshore rupee forwards fell 0.2 percent from
Nov. 1 to 63.29 per dollar, data compiled by Bloomberg show.
Offshore non-deliverable contracts rose 0.6 percent to 63.46.
Forwards are agreements to buy or sell assets at a set price and
date. Non-deliverable contracts are settled in dollars.  To contact the reporter on this story:
